GABAY.eng_example: Get dressed in a hurry so that we won’t be late.
GABAY.ilok_example: Idardaras mo ti agrubbuat tapno ditay magabay.

GABSOON.eng_example: Don’t pile up the rubbish there.
GABSOON.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gabsoonen ti basura dita.

GABUR.definition: to fill up, cover, dump something on or into.
GABUR.eng_example: Don’t fill up that hole which I dug.
GABUR.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gaburan dayta kinalik nga abut.

GABYON.definition: to dig or hit with a hoe.

GADGAD.definition: to whet, to cause to become smooth, e.g. tools.

GAGA.definition: to protect from, lead away from.
GAGA.eng_example: It was he who led me away from danger.
GAGA.ilok_example: Isu ti nangigaga kanyak ti disgrasia.

GAGANGAY.eng_example: The stories written in this book are the usual things that children do every day.
GAGANGAY.ilok_example: Dagiti nailanad nga sarsarita ditoy nga libro, dagitay gagangay nga aramiden dagiti ubbing iti inaldaw.

GAGAR.definition: to wish or desire strongly, to crave.
GAGAR.eng_example: I wish so much to see her.

GAGARA.definition: to be overused, to be used roughly.
to do on purpose, to do intentionally  knowingly.
GAGARA.eng_example: He hurt the child on purpose.
GAGARA.ilok_example: Inggagara na nga sinaktan diay ubing.

GAKAT.definition: to plan  propose to do  carry out.
GAKAT.eng_example: Don’t plan on doing too much wk.
GAKAT.ilok_example: Saan mo unay nga kaaduen ti igakat mo nga trabaho.

GAKGAK.definition: to croak: said of frogs; to produce a similar sound.

GALBA.definition: galvanized iron sheet used for roofing.
GALBA.eng_example: Our house is roofed with galvanized iron sheets.
GALBA.ilok_example: Nagatep ti galba ti balay mi.

GALYERA.definition: cockpit, the place where cockfighting is held.

GALUT.definition: anything used for tying or binding. --SINGDAN.

GALYETAS.definition: a kind of flat round bread.

GAMAT.definition: 1. tendril. 2. arm of cuttlefish, octopus, etc.

GAMER.definition: to mix, blend, mingle; to get mixed up with.
GAMER.eng_example: Don’t get yourself mixed up with evil.
GAMER.ilok_example: Saan mo nga igamer ta bagim ti kinadakes.

GAMGAM.definition: to desire, covet, e.g. a position, an office, etc.

GAMMAL.definition: to grasp, to take hold of firmly with the hand.
GAMMAL.eng_example: Hurry up and grasp that frog.

GAMOLO.definition: to turn over, to turn to the other side.
GAMOLO.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gamoloen dayta ikan.

GAMOLO.definition: to manage, take charge of, be responsible for.
GAMOLO.eng_example: It was he who took charge of our preparation for the festival.
GAMOLO.ilok_example: Isu ti naggamolo ti sagana mi ti piesta.

GAMUD.definition: to bewitch: to influence or affect especially injuriously by witchcraft.
GAMUD.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gamuden ni nanang ko.

MANGGAGAMUD.definition: a person who practices or is familiar with witchcraft.

GAM-UD.eng_example: It is hard to obtain what I am asking from him.
GAM-UD.ilok_example: Narigat nga gamuden ti dawdawatek kenkuana.

GAM-UD.definition: 1. to catch up with, to arrive early for.
GAM-UD.eng_example: I did not arrive early for the beginning of the show. 2. to reach, go as far as.
GAM-UD.ilok_example: Diak nga nagam-udan ti rugi ti pabuya.

GANAB.definition: to gain, to receive as benefit.

GANADOR.definition: 1. a gamecock which has won at least twice. 2. an established winner.

GANAKGAK.definition: to produce a loud, deep and reverberating sound like that of bells.

GANAS.definition: appetite, desire, urge to do something.
GANAS.eng_example: I have no appetite to eat.
GANAS.ilok_example: Awan ti ganas ko nga mangan.

GANAS.eng_example: It is pleasing to eat in an eating place that is clean and neat.
GANAS.ilok_example: Naganas ti mangan iti panganan nga nadalimanek.

GANAS.definition: to enjoy, relish; to find pleasure or satisfaction in doing.

GANAT.definition: to be in a hurry, to hasten.

GAN-AY.definition: to fix fibers ready f weaving.

GANAYGAY.ilok_example: Awan ti ganaygay na nga nagsao.

GANAYGAY.definition: to be lively, full of life, full of spirit, full of enthusiasm.
to animate, to cause to be lively, full of life, etc.

GANDAT.eng_example: That plan of his was rebuffed.

GANSILIO.definition: crotchet, a hooked instrument used in crocheting.
to make by crocheting, to crochet.

GAGANTINGAN.definition: any weighing machine. see under GANTING.

GANUS.definition: 1. immature, unripe, green: said of fruits. 2. young, immature: said of persons.

GANOT.eng_example: Pull off forcibly all those climbing on the fence.
GANOT.ilok_example: Ganotem amin nga kumalkalatkat dita alad.

GANGAT.definition: to light, set fire to, kindle.
GANGAT.eng_example: He does not want to light the lamp.
GANGAT.ilok_example: Saan na kayat nga gangtan diay silaw.

GANGAT.definition: to light or kindle (a lamp, candle, etc.) with another light.

GANGO.definition: to become dry: said of leaves. --cf.

GAO.definition: to draw out food, especially rice, from the pot or pan in order to serve.
GAO.eng_example: Draw out the food so that we can eat.

GAO.definition: to draw out (food) from the pot or pan in order to serve.
GAO.eng_example: Don’t draw that out yet from the pot for it is not yet cooked.
GAO.ilok_example: Saan mo pay nga gaoen dayta ta saan pay nga naluto.

GAPAGAP.definition: to cut into thin slices with a knife moving it as though using a saw.
GAPAGAP.eng_example: Cut that banana trunk into thin slices.

GAPAS.definition: to harvest rice by cutting the upper part of the stalks where the grains are attached with a sickle.
1. to cut the top part of (rice or any other plant) with a sickle. 2. to cut or attack with a sickle.

GAPO.definition: to begin, set about, start; to be about to.
GAPO.eng_example: I am about to go to sleep.

GAPO.definition: to do something for the sake of (someone).
to be done because of, for the sake of, on account of.
GAPO.ilok_example: TA, conj. because, since, inasmuch as, for, as.

NAGGAPPOAM.ilok_example: Where have you been? or; Where did you come from? -a usual greeting equivalent to: How are you?

GARADUGUD.definition: to produce a gurgling or rumbling sound.
GARADUGUD.eng_example: My stomach is producing a rumbling sound.

GARAIGI.definition: 1. to neigh, whinny. 2. to laugh like a horse.

GARAMUGAM.definition: always moving about and touching things.

GARANGOGONG.definition: to slide down into a pit, hole, etc.
to slide (something) down into a pit, hole, etc.
GARANGOGONG.eng_example: You slide down the garbage into the hole.
GARANGOGONG.ilok_example: Igarangogong mo dayta basura dita abut.

GARAPON.definition: a glass jar where bread, sugar, etc. are stored.

GARAW.eng_example: You will fall if you move.

GARAW.definition: 1. to move, to change the place or position of. 2. to touch, molest.
GARAW.eng_example: I will kill you if you molest my daughter.
GARAW.ilok_example: Patayen ka no garawem diay balasang ko.

GARAW.definition: 1. always moving or stirring. 2. always touching someone.

GARES.definition: soft, watery and friable: said especially of squashes, which are considered not very tasty to eat.

GARGARET.definition: pl. furniture, jewels; tools, implements, utensils; household belongings.

GARGARI.definition: to incite, provoke, goad, stir up.
GARGARI.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gargarien dayta pusa.

GARUGAD.definition: to use a file; to rub, smooth or cut away something with a file.
to rub, smooth or cut away with a file; to file.

GARUT.definition: to break loose by breaking or untying its leash or pulling out the tether: said of animals, chickens, etc. on a leash.
to succeed in breaking loose by breaking or untying its leash.
GARUT.eng_example: Tie that chicken well so that it won’t succeed in breaking loose.
GARUT.ilok_example: Igalut mo nga nasayaat dayta manok tapno saan nga makagarut.

GARUT.definition: to snap or break suddenly a string, thread, etc.).

GASANG.definition: hot: producing a burning sensation in the mouth, throat, etc.; pungent; piquant; biting.

NAIGASATAN.definition: blessed with good luck or fortune.

GASANG-GASAT.definition: to take chances, take the risk, go on an adventure.
GASANG-GASAT.eng_example: I will go take my chances in Manila.

GASGAS.definition: to wear off by rubbing; to scrape.
to be worn off by rubbing or friction.

GASTO.eng_example: How much will you spend to go to Manila? --cf.
GASTO.ilok_example: Mano ti gastoen yo nga mapan idiay Manila?

GASTOS.eng_example: What will be spent in having a toilet made is less than the medical expenses. --cf.
GASTOS.ilok_example: Ti gastoen nga agpaaramid iti kasilyas maksay iti gastos nga pagpaagas.

GASUT.ilok_example: SANGAGASUT, one hundred; DUA GASUT, two hundred; TALLO GASUT, three hundred.

GATAD.definition: to set a price or value on, to appraise.

GATANG.eng_example: There is also a chest which was bought by grandfather and grandmother.
GATANG.ilok_example: Adda pay baul nga gatang pay laeng da lolo ken lola.

GATAS.eng_example: That water buffalo will kick you if you try to milk her. 2. to put or add milk to.
GATAS.ilok_example: Kugtaran na ka dayta nuang no padasem nga gatasan.

GATEL.definition: 1. to be itchy. 2. to be hot.

GATUD.definition: to cull, pick, pluck, gather with fingers.
GATUD.eng_example: The tobacco plants can be culled now.

GAWANG.definition: to put a hole or holes on, to perforate.

GAWAT.definition: any period during which food is scarce; a period of drought.

GAW-AT.definition: to reach for; to thrust out or extend the hand to get (something).

GAWAWA.definition: to ask for, request (something) earnestly or urgently.
GAWAWA.eng_example: It is he who is asking for help urgently.

GAWAY.definition: to be able to manage; to be able to conduct or direct affairs, carry on business; to contrive to get along, succeed in handling matters.

GAWGAW.definition: starch, especially corn starch, used primarily for starching clothes.

GAWID.eng_example: If only I did not restrain him he would have killed you.
GAWID.ilok_example: No diko la nga inggawid, pinatay na ka kuma.

GAW-IS.definition: to reach for and cut or hit with a glancing blow.

GAY-AB.definition: to tear, rip by pulling violently.

GAYABANG.definition: to be torn into shreds, to be shredded.

GAYAD.definition: sufficiently long: said of garments, eaves, etc.

GAYADAN.eng_example: She wiped her eyes with the hem of her dress.
GAYADAN.ilok_example: Impunas na ti gayadan ti bado na iti mata na.

GAYAGAY.eng_example: He initiated the construction of a schoolhouse.
GAYAGAY.ilok_example: Ingayagay na ti pannakabangon ti escuela.

GAYAM.definition: a particle expressing mild surprise or wonder about something unexpected or not previously known.
GAYAM.eng_example: I did not know he is our governor.

GAY-AT.definition: to reach for to grasp, to thrust out or extend the hand to grasp (something).
GAY-AT.eng_example: When he reached for my hand to grasp it, I ran away at once.
GAY-AT.ilok_example: Idi gay-aten na ti imak, nagtarayak a dagus.

GAY-AT.definition: to try to do, start to do.
GAY-AT.eng_example: I started to go home but there were still many people.
GAY-AT.ilok_example: Igay-at ko kuma ti agawiden ngem adu pay la ti tao.

GAYYEM.definition: to befriend, to be a friend of (someone).
GAYYEM.eng_example: I want to be your friend.

GEBGEB.definition: to be able to do or manage.
GEBGEB.eng_example: I cannot do all my work.
GEBGEB.ilok_example: Diak nga magebgeban amin nga trabahok.

GEDGED.definition: to cut with a knife but with motions as though using a saw.
GEDGED.eng_example: Cut the neck of that chicken.

GEKGEK.definition: to go deep inside (a forest, a cave, etc.).
GEKGEK.eng_example: Don’t go deep inside lest you get lost.
GEKGEK.ilok_example: Saan kay nga gumekgek ta dikay to mapukaw.

GELGEL.definition: to rub with the hands, as when handwashing clothes.

GEMGEM.definition: to hold, grasp, grip, clasp, clutch.
GEMGEM.eng_example: It was he who grasped my hand.

GEPPAS.definition: to cut with rough sweeping strokes, to slash.

GERRET.definition: to slice; to cut into slices.

GESSAT.definition: to cause (a strong, etc.) to snap or break suddenly; to cut.
GESSAT.eng_example: Cut that fiber that is hanging there.
GESSAT.ilok_example: Gessatem dayta sagut nga agbitbitin dita.

GESSAT.eng_example: The string which I used to tie something snapped.
GESSAT.ilok_example: Nagsat ti tali nga pinaggalut ko.

MAGSAT.definition: TI ANGES or MAGSAT TI BIAG, to die, expire.

GETTA.definition: coconut milk obtained by pressing the grated coconut meat.

GINETTAAN.definition: a native cake usually eaten for mid-afternoon snacks.
GINETTAAN.eng_example: This preparation is boiled until the coconut milk thickens on top.
GINETTAAN.ilok_example: It is made of sliced GABI, bananas, sweet potatoes with coconut milk (GETTA) and sugar.

GETTEB.definition: to snap, break or cut (a string, thread, etc.).
GETTEB.eng_example: Don’t cut the string of my kite.
GETTEB.ilok_example: Saan mo nga getteben ta lubid ti ullaw ko.

GIDDAN.definition: to do something at the same time.
GIDDAN.eng_example: You eat at the same time.

GIDDAN.definition: to do something at the same time with (someone).

GIDDIAT.definition: to be different, unlike, distinct, unequal.

GIDGID.definition: to rub one’s body against (something or someone).
to rub (one’s body) against (something or someone).
GIDGID.eng_example: The pig rubbed its body against the house fence.
GIDGID.ilok_example: Inggidgid diay baboy ti bagi na diay abulog.

GIEM.definition: a particle expressing cautious confidence or uncertainty.
GIEM.eng_example: It seems that what you planted will die.

GILAB.definition: having an eye defect in which the lower eyelid is pulled down.

GIL-AYAB.definition: to burst into flame, to blaze.
GIL-AYAB.eng_example: The fire burst into flame when the wind blew into it.

GIMONG.definition: community, society, group, crowd; any gathering of people.

GINA.definition: to mind, bother about, pay attention to, attend to, take care of.
GINA.eng_example: He did not attend to his sickness, that’s why it became worse.
GINA.ilok_example: Saan na nga ingginggina ti nasakit na isu nga kimmaro.

GIN-AWA.eng_example: I hope our life will become comfortable. 2. to improve or feel better: said of a sick person.
GIN-AWA.ilok_example: Sapay kuma ta gumin-awa met ti biag tayo.

GIRGIR.definition: to be careful about, to take care of.
GIRGIR.eng_example: If you don’t take care of your sickness it will get worse.
GIRGIR.ilok_example: No dimo nga igirgir ta nasakit mo, kumaronto.

GISGIS.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gisgisen dayta peryodiko.

GITA.definition: oily to the taste, e.g. nuts.

GIWANG.definition: to make an opening or hole through; to make a breach in.

GRADO.definition: 1. grade in school; a class organized for the work of a particular year of a school course. 2. a mark indicating a degree of accomplishment in school. 3. a position in a scale of ranks or qualities
to grade, sort, arrange in a scale or ranks of qualities.

GUBANG.definition: coarse, unpolished: said of the texture of cloth, skin, etc.

GUBAT.definition: to have a war, fight, battle.

GUBBUAY.definition: to originate, rise, issue, spring from.
GUBBUAY.eng_example: Water will issue from that crack.

GUBSANG.definition: 1. coarse, rough (to the touch). 2. coarse, ill-mannered: said of a person’s action or manner.

GUDAS.definition: to put an end to, get rid of, eradicate, stop.
GUDAS.eng_example: He put to an end their beautiful friendship.
GUDAS.ilok_example: Ginudas na ti nasayaat nga panaggagayyem da.

GUDDUA.definition: to share, to divide between themselves.
GUDDUA.ilok_example: Agguddua kayo ti maysa nga mansanas.

GUDDUAGUDDUA.definition: to divide into several parts or shares.
GUDDUAGUDDUA.eng_example: They divided into their lands into several parts.

GUDGUD.definition: herpes; an itchy skin disease; mange.

GUGOT.definition: gum: the tissue that surrounds the necks of teeth and covers the alveolar parts of the jaw.

GULGOL.definition: a kind of tree whose macerated bark is used to make hair shampoo.
to wash the hair with this shampoo; to shampoo the hair.
to wash with shampoo, to shampoo (the hair).

GULLUONG.eng_example: His voice resounded when he delivered a speech.
GULLUONG.ilok_example: Gumluong ti timek na nga nagdiskurso.

GULO.definition: to create disorder, confusion and noise.

GUMES.definition: to wash (clothes, etc.) by squeezing in water.

GUMINTANG.definition: to move the arms and hands in different directions as in native dances.
to move (the arms and hands) as in native dances.

GUNDAWAY.definition: 1. privilege, prerogative, distinction. 2. superiority. 3. chance, occasion.
to be given the privilege or distinction (to do something).

GUNNOT.definition: to pull by combing through with the fingers.

GUN-OD.definition: to obtain, get acquire; to earn, win.
GUN-OD.eng_example: It is necessary that you obtain the highest grade.
GUN-OD.ilok_example: Masapul nga gun-odem ti kangatoan nga grado.

GUNGGON.definition: to shake, to cause to quake, to rock.
GUNGGON.eng_example: Don’t rock our house lest it collapse.
GUNGGON.ilok_example: Saan mo nga gunggonen toy balay mi ta dinto marba.

GUNGGUNA.eng_example: God will reward you if you are merciful to your fellow men.
GUNGGUNA.ilok_example: Gunggunaan na kanto ti Dios no naasi ka ti padam nga tao.

GUPED.definition: to cut breadthwise (any elongated object), to cut shorter.
GUPED.eng_example: He will cut that bamboo shorter.

GUPED.ilok_example: Dayta ti nakaguped ti panagasawa da.

GUPUGOP.definition: to saw, cut with a saw.

GUPUNG.definition: to cut off with a knife, a saw, etc.

GURA.definition: to be angered, annoyed or irritated by (something said or done), to hate or dislike (something said or done).
to be angered, annoyed or irritated by (someone or something), to hate or dislike (someone or something).

GURGUR.definition: to refine; to reduce to a pure state; to free from impurities: said of metals.

GURGURMUT.definition: roots of the BALLAIBA which are eaten.

GURIGOR.definition: to have a fever especially due to an infection.

GURONG.definition: the lower part of the leg between the knee and the ankle.

GURRUOD.definition: to thunder, to produce a thunder.

GUSAB.definition: with cut lips, having the lips cut.
to cut the lips (of someone), to cause the lips (of someone) to be cut.
to have one’s lips cut through an accident.

GUSING.definition: 1. harelipped. 2. chipped or notched at the rim: said of pots, plates, etc.

GUSO.definition: to cause to become disorderly, disarrayed, dishevelled, tousled.

GUSUD.definition: to spear, to hit with a spear or a similar instrument.
to use to spear with, to spear into.

GUSUGUS.eng_example: He will rub that board with a wet piece of cloth.
GUSUGUS.ilok_example: Gusugusan na dayta tabla ti nabasa nga lupot.

GUSUGUS.eng_example: He will rub that wet piece of cloth on that board.
GUSUGUS.ilok_example: Igusugus na dayta nabasa nga lupot dita tabla.

GUTAB.definition: 1. to chip the rim of the mouth or edge of (a plate, a bowl, a coconut shell, etc.).
GUTAB.eng_example: Who chipped this coconut shell? 2. to cut (hair) unevenly.

GUTAB.definition: to be chipped along the rim or edge.

GUTAD.definition: to pull with a quick sharp motion, to pull with a flick or a jerk.

GUTTA.definition: to pull hard especially with a jerk, to tug.

GUYAB.definition: to thrust or stick out the tongue at, to make faces at which includes sticking the tongue out.
GUYAB.eng_example: It was Rose who made faces at me.

GUYUGUY.eng_example: That delicious sidedish entices me to eat.
GUYUGUY.ilok_example: Guyuguyen nak nga mangan dayta naimas nga sida.
